04912nam a22005295i 9780520936003DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20022002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209360037 a10.1525/97805209360032doi  a(DE-B1597)520098  a(OCoLC)52996458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML338.8.D53bD54 2002eb 7aMUS0150002bisacsh04a780/.89/9540542211 aDiehl, Keila, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEchoes from Dharamsala :bMusic in the Life of a Tibetan Refugee Community /cKeila Diehl. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (337 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote to the Reader -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Theory at Home and in the Field -- t1. Dharamsala: A Resting Place to Pass Through -- t2. "There Is a Tension in Our Hearts": Constructing the Rich Cultural Heritage of Tibet -- t3. Taking Refuge in (and from) India: Film Songs, Angry Mobs, and Other Exilic Pleasures and Fears -- t4. The West as Surrogate Shangri-La: Rock and Roll and Rangzen as Style and Ideology -- t5. The Nail That Sticks Up Gets Hammered Down: Making Modern Tibetan Music -- t6. "Little Jolmo Bird in the Willow Grove": Crafting Tibetan Song Lyrics -- t7. A Peek Through Ragged Tent Flaps and Heaven's Door: Concerts That Rupture and Bond -- tConclusion: Echoes, Cycles, and Their Implications -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Echoes from Dharamsala, Keila Diehl uses music to understand the experiences of Tibetans living in Dharamsala, a town in the Indian Himalayas that for more than forty years has been home to Tibet's government-in-exile. The Dalai Lama's presence lends Dharamsala's Tibetans a feeling of being "in place," but at the same time they have physically and psychologically constructed Dharamsala as "not Tibet," as a temporary resting place to which many are unable or unwilling to become attached. Not surprisingly, this community struggles with notions of home, displacement, ethnic identity, and assimilation. Diehl's ethnography explores the contradictory realities of cultural homogenization, hybridity, and concern about ethnic purity as they are negotiated in the everyday lives of individuals. In this way, she complicates explanations of culture change provided by the popular idea of "global flow."Diehl's accessible, absorbing narrative argues that the exiles' focus on cultural preservation, while crucial, has contributed to the development of essentialist ideas of what is truly "Tibetan." As a result, "foreign" or "modern" practices that have gained deep relevance for Tibetan refugees have been devalued. Diehl scrutinizes this tension in her discussion of the refugees' enthusiasm for songs from blockbuster Hindi films, the popularity of Western rock and roll among Tibetan youth, and the emergence of a new genre of modern Tibetan music. Diehl's insight into the soundscape of Dharamsala is enriched by her own experiences as the keyboard player for a Tibetan refugee rock group called the Yak Band. Her groundbreaking study reveals the importance of music as a site where official and personal, old and new representations of Tibetan culture meet and where different notions of "Tibetan-ness" are being imagined, performed, and debated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aTibetansxMusicxHistory and criticismxIndiaxDharmsāla. 0aTibetanszIndiazDharmsālaxMusicxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108i